SIMPLE: partner
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Partner
<hw>Part"ner</hw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧rt"n⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[For
<ets>parcener</ets>, influenced by <ets>part</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>One who has a part in anything with an other; a partaker; an
associate; a sharer.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Partner</xex> of his
fortune.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> <specif>Hence:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>A husband or a wife.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Either one of a couple
who dance together.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>One who shares as a member
of a partnership in the management, or in the gains and losses, of a
business.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My other self, the <qex>partner</qex> of my life.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An associate in any business or
occupation; a member of a partnership. See
<er>Partnership</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A framework of
heavy timber surrounding an opening in a deck, to strengthen it for the
support of a mast, pump, capstan, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Dormant partner</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Silent partner</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Dormant</er>,
<pos>a.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Associate; colleague; coadjutor; confederate;
partaker; participator; companion; comrade; mate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Partner</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Partner
<hw>Part"ner</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To associate, to join.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Partnership</ent>⟦br⟧
